{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1773483887747,"sessionID":"ses_31423da25ffebo9V1CTFH0IpgT","part":{"id":"prt_cebe089b9001Jx21GX4QOqpUfO","sessionID":"ses_31423da25ffebo9V1CTFH0IpgT","messageID":"msg_cebe07ab3001CdpfueRlMC6xeO","type":"tool","callID":"toolu_vrtx_019r36rpGRp1vVnm5fRG3suN","tool":"read","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/fulgidus/Documents/wombo-combo-worktrees/wave-detach-audit/src/commands/launch.ts","limit":20,"offset":1107},"output":"<path>/home/fulgidus/Documents/wombo-combo-worktrees/wave-detach-audit/src/commands/launch.ts</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1107:   // Create the TUI — it will auto-refresh and show activity from the monitor\n1108:   //\n1109:   // Detach support: When the user presses Q in the monitor TUI, we no longer\n1110:   // kill agents and exit. Instead, we set a `detached` flag and let the\n1111:   // monitoring loop exit naturally. The caller (cmdTui) then loops back to\n1112:   // the task browser, which shows a \"running wave\" indicator.\n1113:   let detached = false;\n1114:   const tuiRef = { current: null as WomboTUI | null };\n1115:   const startTUI = () => {\n1116:     tuiRef.current = new WomboTUI({\n1117:       state,\n1118:       monitor,\n1119:       projectRoot,\n1120:       interactive: false,\n1121:       config,\n1122:       onQuit: () => {\n1123:           // Detach from the wave monitor — agents keep running in the background.\n1124:           // The monitoring loop checks `detached` and exits, returning control\n1125:           // to the caller (cmdTui main loop or cmdLaunch).\n1126:           flushState(projectRoot, state);\n\n(Showing lines 1107-1126 of 1956. Use offset=1127 to continue.)\n</content>","title":"src/commands/launch.ts","metadata":{"preview":"  // Create the TUI — it will auto-refresh and show activity from the monitor\n  //\n  // Detach support: When the user presses Q in the monitor TUI, we no longer\n  // kill agents and exit. Instead, we set a `detached` flag and let the\n  // monitoring loop exit naturally. The caller (cmdTui) then loops back to\n  // the task browser, which shows a \"running wave\" indicator.\n  let detached = false;\n  const tuiRef = { current: null as WomboTUI | null };\n  const startTUI = () => {\n    tuiRef.current = new WomboTUI({\n      state,\n      monitor,\n      projectRoot,\n      interactive: false,\n      config,\n      onQuit: () => {\n          // Detach from the wave monitor — agents keep running in the background.\n          // The monitoring loop checks `detached` and exits, returning control\n          // to the caller (cmdTui main loop or cmdLaunch).\n          flushState(projectRoot, state);","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"time":{"start":1773483887743,"end":1773483887747}}}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1773483887758,"sessionID":"ses_31423da25ffebo9V1CTFH0IpgT","part":{"id":"prt_cebe082c9001lzBSt0dwlheRFi","sessionID":"ses_31423da25ffebo9V1CTFH0IpgT","messageID":"msg_cebe07ab3001CdpfueRlMC6xeO","type":"text","text":"OK, `setPendingQuestions` checks `isDestroyed()` before touching the popup. And it's just setting `this.pendingQuestions = questions` otherwise. This should be safe.\n\nHowever, to be extra safe and to properly indicate to the monitoring loop that the TUI is gone, let me null out `tuiRef.current` when detaching. Let me update the `onQuit` handlers:","time":{"start":1773483887757,"end":1773483887757}}}
