{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1773484003056,"sessionID":"ses_31423da25ffebo9V1CTFH0IpgT","part":{"id":"prt_cebe24eee001rcYFosLK5nImec","sessionID":"ses_31423da25ffebo9V1CTFH0IpgT","messageID":"msg_cebe2453f001UrLUX02lbB60iZ","type":"step-start","snapshot":"e2e55cda851d0e0139152bcba3688cd00ca27961"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1773484012472,"sessionID":"ses_31423da25ffebo9V1CTFH0IpgT","part":{"id":"prt_cebe24eef001UrdrJZxknUUK8w","sessionID":"ses_31423da25ffebo9V1CTFH0IpgT","messageID":"msg_cebe2453f001UrLUX02lbB60iZ","type":"text","text":"Wait, there's a subtlety. The `skipAutoResume = false` reset should happen AFTER the browser is shown. If I reset it right before showing the quest picker, then when the user launches a wave from the browser and it completes (or they detach), the loop goes back to the top, and since `skipAutoResume = false`, it auto-resumes if there's still a running wave. But that's actually the desired behavior for a newly launched wave! The user just launched from the browser — they expect to see the monitor.\n\nHmm, actually no. After `cmdLaunch` returns (either wave complete or detached), the loop continues to the top. If detached, `hasRunningWave` is still true. We want to show the browser, not auto-resume. So `skipAutoResume` should remain `true` after ANY detach.\n\nLet me think about this differently:\n- `skipAutoResume = true` after any `cmdResume` or `cmdLaunch` returns\n- `skipAutoResume = false` only when the wave actually completes (no more running agents)\n\nActually, the simplest logic: set `skipAutoResume = true` when coming back from any monitor/launch, and the wave is still running. If the wave completed, `hasRunningWave` will be false anyway, so `skipAutoResume` doesn't matter.\n\nLet me also set `skipAutoResume = true` after `cmdLaunch` returns:","time":{"start":1773484012472,"end":1773484012472}}}
