{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1773484089481,"sessionID":"ses_31423da25ffebo9V1CTFH0IpgT","part":{"id":"prt_cebe3a089001TOHoAXHx74RaD7","sessionID":"ses_31423da25ffebo9V1CTFH0IpgT","messageID":"msg_cebe39647001AxSnMCE9GVUEe3","type":"step-start","snapshot":"2be625e83e1dc9ea22c166d9d50d18b4ef9b4430"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1773484114571,"sessionID":"ses_31423da25ffebo9V1CTFH0IpgT","part":{"id":"prt_cebe3a089002OJa3XvDCASMpJ1","sessionID":"ses_31423da25ffebo9V1CTFH0IpgT","messageID":"msg_cebe39647001AxSnMCE9GVUEe3","type":"text","text":"Good. `isWaveComplete` considers `completed`, `verified`, `failed`, `merged` as terminal states. So when all agents finish while the monitor is closed, the triage in `cmdResume` will detect this, the loop won't even enter (since `isWaveComplete` returns true immediately), and the post-wave cleanup runs.\n\nBut wait — there's a subtle issue. When the monitor is closed and agents finish, the monitoring loop in `launch.ts` (or `resume.ts`) is also NOT running (it exited when `detached` was set). So the agent completion callbacks (`onComplete`, `onError`) from the `ProcessMonitor` might not fire because:\n\n1. The `ProcessMonitor` is still alive (it wasn't destroyed)\n2. The callbacks update state in memory\n3. BUT the monitoring loop exited, so `saveState()` might not be called for these late completions\n\nWait, actually — when `detached` is set and the monitoring loop exits, the function returns. The `ProcessMonitor` and the state object go out of scope. But the agents are still running as child processes!\n\nHere's the critical issue: when `launchWaveHeadless` returns due to detach, the agents are still running as **child processes of this process**. The `ProcessMonitor` event handlers are set up to call `onComplete`/`onError` which update the `state` object in memory and call `saveState()`. But when the function returns, those closures still reference the state object...\n\nActually, let me re-think. In JavaScript, closures keep references alive. The `ProcessMonitor` has event listeners on `ChildProcess` objects. These event listeners were registered in the `onComplete`/`onError` callbacks. The ChildProcess 'exit' event will fire when the agent finishes. The callback will:\n1. Update the in-memory state\n2. Call `saveState()` to persist\n\nThis should work because:\n- The ProcessMonitor object is still alive (referenced by the ChildProcess event listeners)\n- The state object is still alive (referenced by the closures)\n- `saveState()` writes to disk\n\nSo when agents complete while the monitor is closed, the state WILL be persisted to disk. When the user re-opens the monitor (`cmdResume`), it will load the fresh state from disk and see the updated statuses.\n\nBUT — there's a problem. The `cmdTui` main loop is still running (it's showing the browser). When `cmdResume` is called from the `monitor` action, it calls `loadState(projectRoot)` which reads from disk. By that point, the in-memory state from the previous `launchWaveHeadless` call may have been updated by the ProcessMonitor callbacks.\n\nActually wait, this should be fine. The ProcessMonitor callbacks update state and call `saveState()` which writes to disk. When `cmdResume` loads state from disk, it gets the latest.\n\nLet me verify that the ProcessMonitor callbacks are still active after the function returns. In `launchWaveHeadless`, the ProcessMonitor is created as a local variable. When the function returns, its references are:\n- The ChildProcess objects hold references to the event listeners\n- The event listeners hold references to the closure (which references the monitor)\n\nSo yes, the ProcessMonitor stays alive as long as child processes are alive. The callbacks will fire. The state will be saved to disk.\n\nHowever, there's another issue: the `launchWaveHeadless` function also spawns fire-and-forget promises for build verification (`handleBuildVerification`) and launching newly-ready agents (`launchAllReady`). These are triggered from the `onComplete` callback. After detach, these will still run because they're background promises.\n\nBut here's a potential problem: if `launchAllReady` tries to spawn new agents after detach, those agents will also be child processes of the current process. The ProcessMonitor will track them. This is actually fine — they'll be monitored by the still-alive ProcessMonitor callbacks.\n\nThe only real concern is: what if the user tries to `cmdResume` while the old ProcessMonitor is still alive and tracking agents? They'd get a second ProcessMonitor tracking the same agents. The triage in `cmdResume` detects \"still alive\" PIDs and calls `monitor.reconnectProcess()` — which creates a new monitor entry. The old ProcessMonitor would still have event listeners on the same ChildProcess objects... but those objects are local to the old function scope. The new ProcessMonitor uses `reconnectProcess()` which just sets up a polling-based check (by PID), not event listeners.\n\nActually, `reconnectProcess` might not work the same way. Let me check:","time":{"start":1773484114570,"end":1773484114570}}}
