+exit to detach (save state, stop TUI, resolve promise)","priority":"high","status":"completed"},{"content":"Modify resume.ts onQuit: change from kill+exit to detach (save state, stop TUI, resolve promise)","priority":"high","status":"completed"},{"content":"Wire up onSwitchToMonitor in tui.ts showBrowser() so Tab key works","priority":"high","status":"completed"},{"content":"Update tui.ts main loop to handle detach-and-return flow (re-enter browser after Q from monitor)","priority":"high","status":"completed"},{"content":"Enhance Task Browser 'running wave' indicator visibility","priority":"medium","status":"completed"},{"content":"Handle edge case: all agents finish while monitor is closed (covered by existing cmdResume triage)","priority":"medium","status":"completed"},{"content":"Handle edge case: mixed success/failure while monitor is closed (covered by existing cmdResume triage)","priority":"medium","status":"completed"},{"content":"Run typecheck (bun run typecheck)","priority":"high","status":"in_progress"},{"content":"Run build (bun run build)","priority":"high","status":"pending"},{"content":"Commit all changes with conventional commit messages","priority":"high","status":"pending"}],"truncated":false},"time":{"start":1773484148177,"end":1773484148178}}}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1773484148190,"sessionID":"ses_31423da25ffebo9V1CTFH0IpgT","part":{"id":"prt_cebe41a26001gS768y6a2rWl7Y","sessionID":"ses_31423da25ffebo9V1CTFH0IpgT","messageID":"msg_cebe411dc001FLltaK7XvoJvkh","type":"text","text":"OK so `reconnectProcess` uses polling, not event listeners. And the old ProcessMonitor's `onComplete` callback would call `saveState()` with the old state reference. The new ProcessMonitor's `onComplete` callback would also try to handle the same event. This could cause a double-handle.\n\nHowever, looking more carefully: when `launchWaveHeadless` returns due to detach, the ChildProcess objects from the old ProcessMonitor are still alive. Their 'exit' events will fire and the old callbacks will run. Then when `cmdResume` is called, it creates a new ProcessMonitor and `reconnectProcess()` starts a polling interval. When the poll detects the PID is dead, it fires `onComplete` again.\n\nBut by the time `cmdResume` is called, the old callbacks may have already handled the completion (set status to \"completed\" and saved state). The triage in `cmdResume` starts by loading state from disk. If the old callback already set the agent to \"completed\", the triage won't call `reconnectProcess` for that agent (it's not in \"running\" status anymore).\n\nThe timing could be tricky, but the design is tolerant of this:\n- If the old callback fires before triage: triage sees \"completed\" status, skips reconnection\n- If triage runs before the old callback: triage sees \"running\" status, reconnects. Then both the old callback and the reconnect poll might fire `onComplete`. But `updateAgent` is idempotent for status changes (setting \"completed\" twice is harmless).\n\nThis is actually fine. The edge cases are handled by the existing recovery/triage logic in `cmdResume`. Let me verify one more thing — the resume.ts monitoring loop also checks `branchHasChanges()` for dead processes, which is the same logic that handles \"agents finished while closed.\"\n\nLet me now think about whether there are any issues with the polling loop in `launch.ts` that we need to address. When `launchWaveHeadless` returns due to detach, the monitoring loop exits. But the ChildProcess event handlers and fire-and-forget promises are still running. These could:\n\n1. Call `saveState()` — writes to disk, which is fine\n2. Call `launchAllReady()` — spawns new agents, which is... hmm\n\nIf `launchAllReady` spawns new agents after the monitoring loop has exited, those agents will be tracked by the old ProcessMonitor but nobody is polling for their completion anymore (the loop exited). Their `onComplete` callbacks will still fire (via ChildProcess events), and those callbacks will `saveState()`. So the state will be persisted.\n\nWhen `cmdResume` is called next, it will:\n1. Load fresh state from disk\n2. Run triage on all agents\n3. Reconnect to alive agents\n4. Start a new monitoring loop\n\nThis should work correctly. The key insight is: **as long as state is persisted to disk, the recovery mechanism in `cmdResume` handles everything.**\n\nLet me now focus on making sure the edge case handling is solid. The existing code in `cmdResume` already handles:\n- Dead agents with no commits → mark failed\n- Dead agents with commits → mark completed → verify build\n- Completed agents → verify build\n- Verified agents → attempt merge\n- Failed agents with retries → re-verify or re-launch\n\nThis covers both \"all agents finish\" and \"mixed success/failure\" cases.","time":{"start":1773484148189,"end":1773484148189}}}
