{"type":"text","timestamp":1773484188399,"sessionID":"ses_31423da25ffebo9V1CTFH0IpgT","part":{"id":"prt_cebe4fef1002LJQijzM23QbH6Y","sessionID":"ses_31423da25ffebo9V1CTFH0IpgT","messageID":"msg_cebe4f4b900129AsHqkGGpXfZ6","type":"text","text":"Good — SIGINT still kills agents in resume.ts too.\n\nNow let me check for one potential issue: when `cmdResume` is called from the \"monitor\" action in `tui.ts`, the SIGINT handler is registered. But if the user presses Ctrl+C while in the browser (not the monitor), the old SIGINT handler from a previous `cmdResume` call might still be active. Let me check if SIGINT handlers accumulate:\n\nActually, `process.on(\"SIGINT\", handler)` adds a new handler each time. So if `cmdResume` is called multiple times, multiple SIGINT handlers accumulate. This could cause issues. But this was already the case before my changes — each call to `cmdResume` or `cmdLaunch` adds SIGINT handlers without removing the old ones. The old handlers reference old state/monitor objects that may be invalid.\n\nHowever, this is a pre-existing issue, not caused by my changes. And in practice, the `process.exit(0)` in the first handler to fire would prevent subsequent handlers from executing. Still, it's worth noting but outside the scope of this task.\n\nLet me now also handle one important consideration: when running `woco launch` or `woco resume` standalone (not through `cmdTui`), pressing Q should still detach without killing agents. This is actually the correct behavior — the user can always `woco resume` to reconnect. The only issue is that the standalone process won't return to a browser — it just exits. But `cmdLaunch` returns normally when detached, and the CLI handler in `index.ts` will exit cleanly.\n\nWait, let me check what happens after `cmdLaunch` returns in the CLI handler:","time":{"start":1773484188399,"end":1773484188399}}}
